## Steps

1. **Target directory layout.** Print an ASCII folder tree for the new or changed capability. Required shape:

   ```
   <capability-root>/<capability-name>/
   ├── <capability>.entity.{{stack.language}}        # types / schemas only
   ├── <capability>.repository.{{stack.language}}    # {{stack.database}} queries only
   ├── <capability>.service.{{stack.language}}       # business logic only
   ├── <capability>.api.{{stack.language}}           # thin {{stack.api_framework}} handler
   ├── <capability>.test.{{stack.language}}          # tests live with the capability
   └── mod.{{stack.language}}                        # single public export point
   ```

   **Forbidden:** any `utils.*`, `helpers.*`, `common/*`, `shared/*`, `lib/*`, `misc/*` introduction. Print the tree explicitly to prove none are present.

2. **Functional core / imperative shell mapping.** State which file(s) are pure (functional core) and which carry I/O (imperative shell). Repository and API are shell; entity is pure; service is pure where possible.

3. **Cross-capability boundaries.** For every other capability this one talks to, name the public export it imports through. Direct internal imports are forbidden — declare the contract.

4. **ADR (Architectural Decision Record).** Write a complete ADR using this skeleton:

   ```markdown
   # ADR.<ID>: <title>

   **Status:** Proposed
   **Date:** {{TODAY}}

   ## Context
   <SLOs, constraints, problem framing>

   ## Decision
   <what we are doing, in one paragraph>

   ## Alternatives considered
   | Option | Pros | Cons | Rejected because |
   |---|---|---|---|

   ## Consequences
   <positive, negative, and follow-up work>

   ## References
   <ADRs, contracts, capability files>
   ```

## Output

Produce in order: directory tree · core/shell map · cross-capability contract list · ADR.

